caption: The first picture is what I ordered The serving is what Rice Bar thought was ok to hand me It closes at 3 and my colleague arrived just after 2 for pickup. Terrible food. I wanted to like it, as I have had Korean and Korean BBQ (yes, the real Korean BBQ) much of my adult life in SF and NYC.  I came here with my family after visiting a nearby museum and saw that this place was rated well.  Before I give critical feedback, I will say that the staff was extremely friendly and the location was clean. My spicy soup broth tasted like fermaldahyde - the kind I used in college when disecting dead animals in biology class.  As a fan of both firm and soft Tofu, I was unpleasantly surprised to find that this resteraunt's Tofu variety fell into neither category - it was some sort of strange hybrid between rubber and soggy tempura.  In general , it felt like they use low quality ingredients and mass production preoteins that they stretch out all week in the fridge. They obviously partner with grubhub to crank out volume during lunch , but the quality of food was terrible.  If Subway sandwiches ever gets into Asian cusine, it would taste just like the food at this place.

I come from a Korean-American family, so I may be biased right out of the gate, my mother makes a killer bulgogi! That being said, I went in with high expectation considering the reviews, I had a hankerin for some gogi! I was feeling their soup variety that day and it looked so good when put together, ramen noodles prepared fresh with a quick swim in what I assume was broth, veg arranged neatly around the edge of the bowl, and then the pile of bulgogi smack dab in the middle, looked so good. Finally I told them to make it spicy, and went with the beef broth for the soup thinking that would be the most flavorful compared to clear and meso, I may have been mistaken. Overall it was pretty lackluster, surprisingly towards the bland side of the flav-o-meter, and the noodles were a bit over al dente. Yes I could've hit it with more of the sauces available, but I feel I shouldn't have to. I may have to return for the kalbi and rice to get a well rounded feel but I'm not sure since my stay in the D.C. area is temporary.

An awesome place to get Bibimbap or Korean noodle bowls with plenty of vegan and gluten-free options. In fact, they have a separate design-your-own Bibimbap menu with gluten-free options! You fill out an order form for either a rice bowl or a noodle bowl (with or without broth), and select toppings (4 veggies included, others are extra) and sauce to include. Or you can choose one of their signature bowls.  I ordered from the gluten-free Bibimbap menu and picked black rice, some veggies, plain tofu, and ground sesame seeds instead of a sauce (you can get their spicy peanut sauce from the condiment and utensils area). It was fast (though, it was somewhat early in the evening so they weren't very busy) and a simple process.  The food was delicious, too! Perhaps a bit more rice than I would normally like (I probably only ate about half the rice provided), but there were plenty of the toppings provided, too. Definitely a filling meal.
